summary: This speaks to me on so many levels. Runaways #21, which you can buy here, is a much more important issue that I expected it to...
caption:
This speaks to me on so many levels.

Runaways #21, which you can buy here, is a much more important issue that I expected it to be. It takes time to have characters deal with some of their own issues that have been building up for some time by now, be itKarolina’s lingering struggle with anxiety or Molly being unable to bear losing so many people while being afraid nobody will like her if she is happy all the time. The book gives some good messages to people who do deal with similar issues. Yes, anxiety will not go away even if you have all the reasons to be happy. And yes, it is okay to just go and be sad, it’s unhealthy trying to be happy all the time. On top of that we also have Chase being the focus of the issue and showing how much he has grown and more or less become the team dad of this group. It was an issue Chase needed and one that showed how much (mostly) consistent and good character development he had over the years to reach the place he is in now.

- Admin

summary: As far as I can tell, the first Spider-Woman to appear in comics was the character of Valerie the Librarian!  Unfortunately her...
caption:
As far as I can tell, the first Spider-Woman to appear in comics was the character of Valerie the Librarian!

Unfortunately her lack of notoriety would come from her only appearing as Spider-Woman in one issue, and that issue being in a series called Spidey Super Stories, which was a collaboration with The Electric Company. It was aimed at very young kids and wasn’t set in the main 616 continuity, so she was very promptly forgotten about.

I’d honestly love to see her appear in a crossover event, if not just for some out-of-place puns and lessons about teamwork.
